esistance Society -- tChapter 15. The Moderate Pacifists and the League of Universal Brotherhood -- tChapter 16. The Ebbing of the Pacifist Impulse -- tPart IV: Pacifism in the American Civil War -- tChapter 17. The Civil War and the Antebellum Pacifists -- tChapter 18. The Quakers in the Civil War -- tChapter 19. Mennonites and Brethren in the Civil War -- tChapter 20. Religious Pacifism outside the Major Historic Peace Sects, 1861-1865 -- tPart V. Pacifism between the Civil War and the First World War -- tChapter 21. The Quaker Peace Testimony, 1865-1914 -- tChapter 22. Non-Quaker Sectarian Pacifism in an Era of Peace, 1865-1914 -- tChapter 23. The Reemergence of Nonsectarian Pacifism -- tConclusion -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCalled "a pioneer work of the first importance" by Staughton Lynd, this book traces the history of pacifism in America from colonial times to the start of World War I. The author describes how the immigrant peace sects-Quaker, Mennonite, and Dunker -faced the challenges of a hostile environment. The peace societies that sprang up after 1815 form the subject of the next section, with particular attention focused upon the American Peace Society and Garrison's New England Non-Resistance Society. A series of chapters on the reactions of these sects and societies to the Civil War, the neglect of pacifism in the postwar period, and the beginnings of a renewal in the years before the outbreak of war in Europe bring the book to a close. The emphasis on the institutional aspects of the movement is balanced throughout by a rich mine of accounts about the experiences of individual pacifists.Originally published in 1968.The Princeton Legacy Library uses the latest print-on-demand technology to again make available previously out-of-print books from the distinguished backlist of Princeton University Press. These editions preserve the o